    "ocr_text": "June 3, 1909.

Mr. J. Legien, Secretary,
National Centers of Trade Unions,
S. O. 16, Engel-Ufer 15, Berlin, Germany.

Dear Sir and Brother:

Your last letter received and I held it for reply because
I expected almost any time from day to day that I would receive
your cablegram. The cablegram came today in which you inform me
that the International Conference will be held in Paris August 30th,
and I want to thank you for the information. Of course, nothing
unforeseen occurring, I shall be in Paris in attendance at the
conference.

In the course of a few days I shall write you and give you
an approximate itinerary of my trip through the several European
countries. I think it would be safe to assume that I will visit
Hamburg and Berlin in the letter part of July. I shall in the course
of a few days try to give you an approximate idea of the dates and
places that I shall visit. Of course, you understand that one
cannot so easily make an absolute definite itinerary from here because
I am so crowded for time and with work as well as my lack of ac-
quaintance with the schedules of European trains and boats, and the
fact of the arrangements of local men must also be taken into con-
sideration and a margin left either way.

There were a few propositions that I should like to have
submitted for consideration and to be placed upon the agenda that I",
